<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<h1>Ikhw&#257;n al-Saf&#257;&rsquo;</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Tue Apr 22, 2008; substantive revision Fri Aug 29, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
The Ikhw&#257;n al-Saf&#257;&rsquo; or &ldquo;Brethren of
Purity&rdquo;, as their name is commonly translated, are the authors
of one of the most complete Medieval encyclopedias of sciences,
antecedent at least two centuries to the best known in the Latin world
(by Alexander Neckham, Thomas de Cantimpr&eacute;, Vincent de
Beauvais, Bartholomaeus Anglicus, all dating back to the 13th
century). The &ldquo;encyclopedia&rdquo; is a collection of Epistles,
the Arabic title of which is <em>Ras&#257;&rsquo;il Ikhw&#257;n
al-Saf&#257;&rsquo; wa Khull&#257;n al-Waf&#257;&rsquo;</em>
(Epistles of the Pure Brethren and the Sincere Friends). It consists
of extremely heterogeneous materials, reworked to represent the whole
educational training intended for an <em>&eacute;lite</em> (see
later). It is very well known, and a great deal of research into it
has been done by Eastern and Western scholars, but the variety of
topics addressed and the questions raised as to the identity and
ideology of its authors remain unsolved. In an isolated form, and
under a false attribution, some of these treatises came to the Latin
Middle Ages through the Spanish version by Maslama
al-Majr&#299;t&#299;, which is traditionally placed at the
beginnings of the 11th century. This already discussed chronology
(Carusi 2000, 494&ndash;500) is recently questioned by several
scholars. The development of research in this direction was encouraged
by the pioneer study, Fierro 1996, part. 94 and 106&ndash;108; cf.
also Hamdani 1978, 350; Hamdani, Soufan 2019, 11&ndash;12 (see
infra).</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
<ul>
<li><a href="#Aut">1. Authorship</a></li>
<li><a href="#NamDat">2. Naming and dating</a></li>
<li><a href="#IdeCom">3. Ideological commitment</a></li>
<li><a href="#ExtCor">4. The extant <em>corpus</em></a></li>
